    <section class="lx-faq">
      <div class="lx-section-head">
        <p class="lx-kicker">FAQ</p>
        <h2>Common questions about choosing a Yunnan destination</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="lx-faq-list">
        <details class="lx-faq-item" open>
          <summary>Which Yunnan destination is best for first-time visitors?</summary>
          <div class="lx-faq-answer">
            Kunming is often the easiest starting point for a first Yunnan trip because it combines convenient arrival, a mild climate, and access to both city highlights and classic day trips. Dali is also a strong first choice for travelers who prefer a slower and more scenic base.
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="lx-faq-item">
          <summary>Should I choose Dali, Lijiang, Shangri-La, or Xishuangbanna?</summary>
          <div class="lx-faq-answer">
            Choose Dali for lakeside slowness, Bai culture, and restorative scenery. Choose Lijiang for old-town atmosphere and iconic mountain imagery. Choose Shangri-La for Tibetan cultural depth, plateau landscapes, and a more elevated travel mood. Choose Xishuangbanna for tropical warmth, rainforest landscapes, Dai culture, and a slower, more exotic southern Yunnan atmosphere.
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="lx-faq-item">
          <summary>How many destinations should I include in one Yunnan trip?</summary>
          <div class="lx-faq-answer">
            For many travelers, two to three destinations is the most comfortable balance. A shorter trip may combine Kunming and Dali, while a longer classic route often adds Lijiang, Shangri-La, or Xishuangbanna depending on your pace and interests.
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="lx-faq-item">
          <summary>Is Xishuangbanna worth adding to a classic Yunnan itinerary?</summary>
          <div class="lx-faq-answer">
            Yes, especially if you want contrast. Xishuangbanna adds tropical rainforest scenery, Dai culture, temple architecture, and warm-weather slow travel, which feels completely different from the higher-altitude mood of central and northwestern Yunnan.
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="lx-faq-item">
          <summary>Can I customize a Yunnan trip across multiple destinations?</summary>
          <div class="lx-faq-answer">
            Yes. If you already know the destinations you want, Lynxtour’s bespoke planning page is the best next step for shaping a private route around your pace, hotel style, interests, and logistics.
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </section>
